I do feel there is a collective grieving at the unfairness of it all.

We're stuck in a weird in between generation where information was just getting out to us and now in adulthood, we are now JUST getting the best information available and the lost years are no one's fault exactly.
... But those years are still gone.

Technology was only JUST starting to take off and computers in the home were only just becoming common. I didn't get my first home computer until I was 12. And the tech we need to know is already evolving far beyond us, when younger gens get to grow up with this stuff.

Example: ADD/ADHD awareness was really JUST getting out there, and even then it was considered a "boys' disease" where kids ran around all the time and were disruptive. Other kinds of ADHD were largely unknown and girls with ADHD were unwittingly left in the dust.
Also, looking back in a very general sense, a lot of 90s kids got stuck in a in-between state where we COULDN'T get the help we needed because the resources weren't available.

I grew up as the good, quiet, smart child who was "just lazy" and "needed to apply herself more" in school. But you could push me off a skyscraper before I gave a shit about economics lol. I physically was just UNABLE to do work for stuff I didn't care about.

ADHD is stereotyped as being hyperactive and running around and being physically disruptive, which is why it took me well into adulthood to get diagnosed. I'm literally the opposite of that lol. My lack of attention is very internal.
I'll never know. Never know. So I try to spread as much info about ADHD as I can so I can maybe prevent some lost years for others.

I try not to dwell on it because, well, I did The Thing and got my degree and all that jazz, but, like, what could I have done for myself if I had known and had just gotten that little bit of extra help?
Not even counting the fact that I have a physical disorder that restricted what I could do, homework-wise.

Especially since I went to a college that required Gen Ed classes on top of whatever major you had. That's a FANTASTIC way to put me in a class I couldn't give two shits about and thus never did the work until last minute.

Oof, I can't tell you how much I wish I had been diagnosed with ADHD sooner. Like, when I was still in school. I probably would've been a lot better off, because I loved to learn, but I was a terrible student lol.
